      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Is a Material Fact in Queensland Property Sales?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Seller and agent disclosure obligations, common examples that arise at listing, and how to handle known issues before your property goes to market.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The concept of a material fact is one of the most important legal ideas in Queensland property transactions, and one of the most commonly misunderstood by sellers. Understanding what you are required to disclose, why the obligation exists, and how to manage known issues sensibly before listing will protect you legally and usually produce a better sale outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal definition</h2>
      <p>Under the Property Occupations Act 2014 (Qld), a material fact is information that a seller or their agent knows, or ought reasonably to know, that would be likely to influence a buyer's decision to purchase the property or the price they are prepared to pay. This is a deliberately broad definition. It is not limited to physical defects; it extends to any information that a reasonable buyer would consider relevant to the transaction.</p>

      <p>Both the seller and the agent have independent disclosure obligations. An agent cannot simply pass on only what the seller tells them and consider their duty discharged. If an agent knows about a material fact independently, they are obligated to disclose it. In practice this means the seller-agent relationship on disclosure needs to be transparent in both directions. Sellers should tell their agent everything material; agents should ask the right questions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common examples of material facts in Queensland</h2>
      <p>The most frequently encountered material facts in Queensland residential sales fall into several broad categories. Structural defects are the most obvious: a known foundation issue, roof failure, termite damage, or building work carried out without the required approvals. If you know about a structural problem, it must be disclosed. This is true even if you intend to sell the property as is and price it accordingly.</p>

      <p>Flood and water ingress history is increasingly common in Brisbane's inner east following the 2011 and 2022 events. A property that has experienced flooding, even if the flood was not riverine and does not appear in a council overlay, has a history that buyers would consider material. Similarly, chronic dampness, drainage problems, or stormwater issues that you have managed over the years are worth disclosing rather than hoping a buyer does not notice.</p>

      <p>Neighbourhood disputes are often overlooked by sellers who assume they are private matters. In Queensland, a dispute with a neighbour that has escalated to a formal process, or where there is an ongoing pattern of conflict that a buyer would reasonably want to know about, can be a material fact. The threshold is whether the issue would affect a reasonable buyer's decision. A noise complaint you filed once three years ago is unlikely to meet that threshold. A boundary dispute involving lawyers and ongoing tension is a different matter.</p>

      <p>Deaths on the property occupy a distinct category. There is no bright-line statutory rule that says all deaths must be disclosed, but a death that occurred in the property within a recent period, or that was violent or occurred under circumstances that would concern a buyer, is generally treated as material. The appropriate question is whether a reasonable buyer would want to know. If you are uncertain, the safer approach is to disclose and let the buyer decide how to weigh it.</p>

      <p>Development plans and infrastructure proposals in the surrounding area can also be material. If you are aware that a significant development is proposed nearby, that an infrastructure project will affect your street, or that a planning scheme change has been flagged for your area, a buyer who would make a different decision with that information deserves to have it.</p>

      <p>Contamination is less common in residential settings but arises where a property has been used for certain commercial or industrial purposes, or where a previous owner operated activities that may have left soil or groundwater contamination. This is a category where professional advice before listing is advisable if there is any historical reason for concern.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent obligations versus seller obligations</h2>
      <p>Sellers are required to complete the property disclosure statement as part of the contract of sale. This document asks specific questions about the property's condition, building approvals, dispute history, and other material matters. Answering honestly is not optional; providing false information on this document creates exposure to claims of misrepresentation.</p>

      <p>Agents carry a separate, concurrent obligation. Under the Property Occupations Act and the Real Estate Institute of Queensland's professional standards, an agent who becomes aware of a material fact cannot simply stay silent because the seller did not instruct them to disclose it. An agent who suppresses a known material fact to avoid jeopardising a sale is at risk of disciplinary action and personal liability.</p>

      <p>This shared obligation structure means that the best approach for sellers is to have a thorough conversation with their agent before listing, covering everything they know about the property's history. A good agent will ask the right questions and help you understand what is likely to be material and what is not, rather than leaving you to guess. It also means that sellers who attempt to conceal information from their agent are creating a situation where neither the seller nor the agent is protected.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Consequences of non-disclosure</h2>
      <p>A buyer who discovers an undisclosed material fact before settlement may have grounds to terminate the contract. A buyer who discovers it after settlement may have grounds for a damages claim. In either case, the cost to the seller of non-disclosure will typically exceed whatever short-term advantage they imagined they were gaining by concealing the information.</p>

      <p>The reputational consequences in a local market should not be underestimated either. Brisbane's inner-east property market is a tight community. Buyers talk to other buyers, and agents know each other. A seller whose non-disclosure surfaces during a sale or after settlement will find subsequent transactions more difficult and their agent's willingness to support them reduced.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to handle known material facts before listing</h2>
      <p>The practical approach to known material facts is to address what you can, disclose what you cannot, and price accordingly. If you have a known structural defect, getting a building report and a repair quote before you go to market gives you control over the narrative. You can present the issue with full information and a quoted cost to fix, rather than having it surface at a buyer's inspection in a more alarming form.</p>

      <p>For issues you cannot or choose not to remediate, clear disclosure from the outset produces better results than discovery mid-campaign. Buyers who know about an issue from the start factor it into their initial offer. Buyers who discover an issue after becoming emotionally invested in the property and going through pre-approval use it as a reason to renegotiate, often more aggressively than the issue warrants.</p>

      <p>The drafting of disclosure language in your marketing materials and contract annexures is worth spending time on with your agent and solicitor. Accurate, clearly worded disclosure that contextualises an issue without sensationalising it is a skill. The aim is informed consent, not alarm.</p>

